🧱 1. Pantheon Entry Schema (the backbone)

This is your equivalent of a Pokédex page.

PantheonEntry.json (v1)

{
  "id": "uuid",
  "title": "Constraint Stacks for AI Output",
  "type": "method",
  "summary": "A structured prompting system that improves output quality via layered constraints.",
  
  "invariant": "Quality improves when the probability space is constrained and evaluated.",
  
  "mechanism": [
    "Define objective",
    "Assign role",
    "Add constraints",
    "Specify evaluation criteria",
    "Run critique loop"
  ],
  
  "inputs": [
    "task definition",
    "context",
    "constraints"
  ],
  
  "outputs": [
    "structured high-quality responses"
  ],
  
  "use_cases": [
    "prompt engineering",
    "strategy writing",
    "product design"
  ],
  
  "constraints": [
    "requires clear objective",
    "increased upfront effort"
  ],
  
  "failure_modes": [
    "over-constraining reduces creativity",
    "vague criteria produce generic output"
  ],
  
  "variants": [
    "sniper loop",
    "commander intent stack"
  ],
  
  "relations": {
    "builds_on": ["prompt engineering"],
    "related_to": ["evaluation loops", "multi-agent systems"]
  },
  
  "confidence": 0.82,
  "status": "active",
  
  "created_at": "timestamp",
  "updated_at": "timestamp"
}


⸻

⚙️ Why this schema works

It forces:
	•	clarity (summary + invariant)
	•	mechanism (how it works)
	•	usefulness (inputs/outputs/use cases)
	•	honesty (failure modes)
	•	evolution (variants + relations)

Most systems skip at least half of these.

That’s why they don’t compound.

